#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:75
msgid "INVOKE_RUN"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:77
msgid ""
"Whether we will run the main() function. Disable if you embed the generated "
"code in your own, and will call main() yourself at the right time (which you "
"can do with Module.callMain(), with an optional parameter of commandline "
"args)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:86
msgid "EXIT_RUNTIME"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:88
msgid ""
"If 0, support for shutting down the runtime is not emitted into the build. "
"This means that the program is not quit when main() completes, but execution "
"will yield to the event loop of the JS environment, allowing event handlers "
"to run afterwards. If 0, C++ global destructors will not be emitted into the "
"build either, to save on code size. Calling exit() will throw an unwinding "
"exception, but will not shut down the runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:95
msgid ""
"Set this to 1 if you do want to retain the ability to shut down the program. "
"If 1, then completing main() will by default call exit(), unless a refcount "
"keeps the runtime alive. Call emscripten_exit_with_live_runtime() to finish "
"main() while keeping the runtime alive. Calling emscripten_force_exit() will "
"shut down the runtime, invoking atexit()s, and flushing stdio streams. This "
"setting is controlled automatically in :ref:`STANDALONE_WASM` mode:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:102
msgid "For a command (has a main function) this is always 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:103
msgid "For a reactor (no main function) this is always 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:105
msgid ""
"For more details, see documentation for emscripten_force_exit() and "
"emscripten_exit_with_live_runtime()."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:113
msgid "STACK_SIZE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:115
msgid ""
"The total stack size. There is no way to enlarge the stack, so this value "
"must be large enough for the program's requirements. If assertions are on, "
"we will assert on not exceeding this, otherwise, it will fail silently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:120
msgid "Default value: 64*1024"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:125
msgid "MALLOC"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:127
msgid "What malloc()/free() to use, out of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:129
msgid "dlmalloc - a powerful general-purpose malloc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:130
msgid "emmalloc - a simple and compact malloc designed for emscripten"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:131
msgid "emmalloc-debug - use emmalloc and add extra assertion checks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:132
msgid ""
"emmalloc-memvalidate - use emmalloc with assertions+heap consistency "
"checking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:134
msgid "emmalloc-verbose - use emmalloc with assertions + verbose logging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:135
msgid ""
"emmalloc-memvalidate-verbose - use emmalloc with assertions + heap "
"consistency checking + verbose logging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:137
msgid ""
"mimalloc - a powerful multithreaded allocator. This is recommended in large "
"applications that have malloc() contention, but it is larger and uses more "
"memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:140
msgid ""
"none - no malloc() implementation is provided, but you must implement "
"malloc() and free() yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:143
msgid ""
"dlmalloc is necessary for split memory and other special modes, and will be "
"used automatically in those cases. In general, if you don't need one of "
"those special modes, and if you don't allocate very many small objects, you "
"should use emmalloc since it's smaller. Otherwise, if you do allocate many "
"small objects, dlmalloc is usually worth the extra size. dlmalloc is also a "
"good choice if you want the extra security checks it does (such as noticing "
"metadata corruption in its internal data structures, which emmalloc does not "
"do)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:152
msgid "Default value: \"dlmalloc\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:157
msgid "ABORTING_MALLOC"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:159
msgid ""
"If 1, then when malloc would fail we abort(). This is nonstandard behavior, "
"but makes sense for the web since we have a fixed amount of memory that must "
"all be allocated up front, and so (a) failing mallocs are much more likely "
"than on other platforms, and (b) people need a way to find out how big that "
"initial allocation (INITIAL_MEMORY) must be. If you set this to 0, then you "
"get the standard malloc behavior of returning NULL (0) when it fails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:167
msgid ""
"Setting ALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH turns this off, as in that mode we default to "
"the behavior of trying to grow and returning 0 from malloc on failure, like "
"a standard system would. However, you can still set this flag to override "
"that.  This is a mostly-backwards-compatible change. Previously this option "
"was ignored when growth was on. The current behavior is that growth turns it "
"off by default, so for users that never specified the flag nothing changes. "
"But if you do specify it, it will have an effect now, which it did not "
"previously. If you don't want that, just stop passing it in at link time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:176
msgid ""
"Note that this setting does not affect the behavior of operator new in C++. "
"This function will always abort on allocation failure if exceptions are "
"disabled. If you want new to return 0 on failure, use it with std::nothrow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:186
msgid "INITIAL_HEAP"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:188
msgid ""
"The initial amount of heap memory available to the program.  This is the "
"memory region available for dynamic allocations via `sbrk`, `malloc` and "
"`new`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:191
msgid ""
"Unlike INITIAL_MEMORY, this setting allows the static and dynamic regions of "
"your program's memory to independently grow. In most cases we recommend "
"using this setting rather than `INITIAL_MEMORY`. However, this setting does "
"not work for imported memories (e.g. when dynamic linking is used)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:196
msgid "Default value: 16777216"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:201
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1476
msgid "INITIAL_MEMORY"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:203
msgid ""
"The initial amount of memory to use. Using more memory than this will cause "
"us to expand the heap, which can be costly with typed arrays: we need to "
"copy the old heap into a new one in that case. If ALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH is "
"set, this initial amount of memory can increase later; if not, then it is "
"the final and total amount of memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:209
msgid ""
"By default, this value is calculated based on INITIAL_HEAP, STACK_SIZE, as "
"well the size of static data in input modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:212
msgid "(This option was formerly called TOTAL_MEMORY.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:214
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:303
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:338
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3108
msgid "Default value: -1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:219
msgid "MAXIMUM_MEMORY"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:221
msgid ""
"Set the maximum size of memory in the wasm module (in bytes). This is only "
"relevant when ALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH is set, as without growth, the size of "
"INITIAL_MEMORY is the final size of memory anyhow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:225
msgid ""
"Note that the default value here is 2GB, which means that by default if you "
"enable memory growth then we can grow up to 2GB but no higher. 2GB is a "
"natural limit for several reasons:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:229
msgid ""
"If the maximum heap size is over 2GB, then pointers must be unsigned in "
"JavaScript, which increases code size. We don't want memory growth builds to "
"be larger unless someone explicitly opts in to >2GB+ heaps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:232
msgid ""
"Historically no VM has supported more >2GB+, and only recently (Mar 2020) "
"has support started to appear. As support is limited, it's safer for people "
"to opt into >2GB+ heaps rather than get a build that may not work on all VMs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:237
msgid "To use more than 2GB, set this to something higher, like 4GB."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:239
msgid "(This option was formerly called WASM_MEM_MAX and BINARYEN_MEM_MAX.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:241
msgid "Default value: 2147483648"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:246
msgid "ALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:248
msgid ""
"If false, we abort with an error if we try to allocate more memory than we "
"can (INITIAL_MEMORY). If true, we will grow the memory arrays at runtime, "
"seamlessly and dynamically. See https://code.google.com/p/v8/issues/detail?"
"id=3907 regarding memory growth performance in chrome. Note that growing "
"memory means we replace the JS typed array views, as once created they "
"cannot be resized. (In wasm we can grow the Memory, but still need to create "
"new views for JS.) Setting this option on will disable ABORTING_MALLOC, in "
"other words, ALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH enables fully standard behavior, of both "
"malloc returning 0 when it fails, and also of being able to allocate more "
"memory from the system as necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:266
msgid "MEMORY_GROWTH_GEOMETRIC_STEP"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:268
msgid ""
"If ALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH is true, this variable specifies the geometric "
"overgrowth rate of the heap at resize. Specify "
"MEMORY_GROWTH_GEOMETRIC_STEP=0 to disable overgrowing the heap at all, or e."
"g. MEMORY_GROWTH_GEOMETRIC_STEP=1.0 to double the heap (+100%) at every grow "
"step. The larger this value is, the more memory the WebAssembly heap "
"overreserves to reduce performance hiccups coming from memory resize, and "
"the smaller this value is, the more memory is conserved, at the performance "
"of more stuttering when the heap grows. (profiled to be on the order of ~20 "
"msecs)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:277
msgid "Default value: 0.20"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:282
msgid "MEMORY_GROWTH_GEOMETRIC_CAP"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:284
msgid ""
"Specifies a cap for the maximum geometric overgrowth size, in bytes. Use "
"this value to constrain the geometric grow to not exceed a specific rate. "
"Pass MEMORY_GROWTH_GEOMETRIC_CAP=0 to disable the cap and allow unbounded "
"size increases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:289
msgid "Default value: 96*1024*1024"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:294
msgid "MEMORY_GROWTH_LINEAR_STEP"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:296
msgid ""
"If ALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH is true and MEMORY_GROWTH_LINEAR_STEP == -1, then "
"geometric memory overgrowth is utilized (above variable). Set "
"MEMORY_GROWTH_LINEAR_STEP to a multiple of WASM page size (64KB), eg. 16MB "
"to replace geometric overgrowth rate with a constant growth step size. When "
"MEMORY_GROWTH_LINEAR_STEP is used, the variables "
"MEMORY_GROWTH_GEOMETRIC_STEP and MEMORY_GROWTH_GEOMETRIC_CAP are ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:308
msgid "MEMORY64"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:310
msgid ""
"The \"architecture\" to compile for. 0 means the default wasm32, 1 is the "
"full end-to-end wasm64 mode, and 2 is wasm64 for clang/lld but lowered to "
"wasm32 in Binaryen (such that it can run on wasm32 engines, while internally "
"using i64 pointers). Nowadays we recommend using the more standard `-m64` or "
"`--target=wasm64` flags, which do the same thing. Assumes WASM_BIGINT."
msgstr ""

