#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1753
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:2165
msgid "This setting is deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:327
msgid "INITIAL_TABLE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:329
msgid ""
"Sets the initial size of the table when MAIN_MODULE or SIDE_MODULE is used "
"(and not otherwise). Normally Emscripten can determine the size of the table "
"at link time, but in SPLIT_MODULE mode, wasm-split often needs to grow the "
"table, so the table size baked into the JS for the instrumented build will "
"be too small after the module is split. This is a hack to allow users to "
"specify a large enough table size that can be consistent across both builds. "
"This setting may be removed at any time and should not be used except in "
"conjunction with SPLIT_MODULE and dynamic linking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:343
msgid "ALLOW_TABLE_GROWTH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:345
msgid ""
"If true, allows more functions to be added to the table at runtime. This is "
"necessary for dynamic linking, and set automatically in that mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:353
msgid "GLOBAL_BASE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:355
msgid ""
"Where global data begins; the start of static memory. A GLOBAL_BASE of 1024 "
"or above is useful for optimizing load/store offsets, as it enables the --"
"low-memory-unused pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:359
msgid "Default value: 1024"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:364
msgid "TABLE_BASE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:366
msgid ""
"Where table slots (function addresses) are allocated. This must be at least "
"1 to reserve the zero slot for the null pointer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:374
msgid "USE_CLOSURE_COMPILER"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:376
msgid "Whether closure compiling is being run on this output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:383
msgid "CLOSURE_WARNINGS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:385
msgid ""
"Deprecated: Use the standard warnings flags instead. e.g. ``-Wclosure``, ``-"
"Wno-closure``, ``-Werror=closure``. options: 'quiet', 'warn', 'error'. If "
"set to 'warn', Closure warnings are printed out to console. If set to "
"'error', Closure warnings are treated like errors, similar to -Werror "
"compiler flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:393
msgid "Default value: 'quiet'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:398
msgid "IGNORE_CLOSURE_COMPILER_ERRORS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:400
msgid "Ignore closure warnings and errors (like on duplicate definitions)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:407
msgid "DECLARE_ASM_MODULE_EXPORTS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:409
msgid ""
"If set to 1, each wasm module export is individually declared with a "
"JavaScript \"var\" definition. This is the simple and recommended approach. "
"However, this does increase code size (especially if you have many such "
"exports), which can be avoided in an unsafe way by setting this to 0. In "
"that case, no \"var\" is created for each export, and instead a loop (of "
"small constant code size, no matter how many exports you have) writes all "
"the exports received into the global scope. Doing so is dangerous since such "
"modifications of the global scope can confuse external JS minifier tools, "
"and also things can break if the scope the code is in is not the global "
"scope (e.g. if you manually enclose them in a function scope)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:425
msgid "INLINING_LIMIT"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:427
msgid ""
"If set to 1, prevents inlining. If 0, we will inline normally in LLVM. This "
"does not affect the inlining policy in Binaryen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:430
msgid "Only applicable during compilation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:437
msgid "SUPPORT_BIG_ENDIAN"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:439
msgid ""
"If set to 1, perform an acorn pass that converts each HEAP access into a "
"function call that uses DataView to enforce LE byte order for HEAP buffer; "
"This makes generated JavaScript run on BE as well as LE machines. (If 0, "
"only LE systems are supported). Does not affect generated wasm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:444
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:2831
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3214
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3249
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3369
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3381
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3395
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3446
msgid "This is an experimental setting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:451
msgid "SAFE_HEAP"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:453
msgid ""
"Check each write to the heap, for example, this will give a clear error on "
"what would be segfaults in a native build (like dereferencing 0). See "
"runtime_safe_heap.js for the actual checks performed. Set to value 1 to test "
"for safe behavior for both Wasm+Wasm2JS builds. Set to value 2 to test for "
"safe behavior for only Wasm builds. (notably, Wasm-only builds allow "
"unaligned memory accesses. Note, however, that on some architectures "
"unaligned accesses can be very slow, so it is still a good idea to verify "
"your code with the more strict mode 1)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:467
msgid "SAFE_HEAP_LOG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:469
msgid "Log out all SAFE_HEAP operations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:476
msgid "EMULATE_FUNCTION_POINTER_CASTS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:478
msgid ""
"Allows function pointers to be cast, wraps each call of an incorrect type "
"with a runtime correction.  This adds overhead and should not be used "
"normally.  Aside from making calls not fail, this tries to convert values as "
"best it can.  We use 64 bits (i64) to represent values, as if we wrote the "
"sent value to memory and loaded the received type from the same memory "
"(using truncs/extends/ reinterprets). This means that when types do not "
"match the emulated values may not match (this is true of native too, for "
"that matter - this is all undefined behavior). This approach appears good "
"enough to support Python (the original motivation for this feature) and Glib "
"(the continued motivation)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:494
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3316
msgid "EXCEPTION_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:496
msgid "Print out exceptions in emscriptened code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:503
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3313
msgid "LIBRARY_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:505
msgid ""
"Print out when we enter a library call (library*.js). You can also unset "
"runtimeDebug at runtime for logging to cease, and can set it when you want "
"it back. A simple way to set it in C++ is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:516
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3317
msgid "SYSCALL_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:518
msgid ""
"Print out all musl syscalls, including translating their numeric index to "
"the string name, which can be convenient for debugging. (Other system calls "
"are not numbered and already have clear names; use :ref:`LIBRARY_DEBUG` to "
"get logging for all of them.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:528
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3319
msgid "SOCKET_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:530
msgid "Log out socket/network data transfer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:537
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3312
msgid "DYLINK_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:539
msgid "Log dynamic linker information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:546
msgid "FS_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:548
msgid "Register file system callbacks using trackingDelegate in library_fs.js"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:555
msgid "SOCKET_WEBRTC"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:557
msgid ""
"As well as being configurable at compile time via the \"-s\" option the "
"WEBSOCKET_URL and WEBSOCKET_SUBPROTOCOL settings may be configured at run "
"time via the Module object e.g. Module['websocket'] = {subprotocol: 'base64, "
"binary, text'}; Module['websocket'] = {url: 'wss://', subprotocol: "
"'base64'}; You can set 'subprotocol' to null, if you don't want to specify "
"it. Run time configuration may be useful as it lets an application select "
"multiple different services."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:571
msgid "WEBSOCKET_URL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:573
msgid ""
"A string containing either a WebSocket URL prefix (ws:// or wss://) or a "
"complete RFC 6455 URL - \"ws[s]:\" \"//\" host [ \":\" port ] path [ \"?\" "
"query ]. In the (default) case of only a prefix being specified the URL will "
"be constructed from prefix + addr + ':' + port where addr and port are "
"derived from the socket connect/bind/accept calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:579
msgid "Default value: 'ws://'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:584
msgid "PROXY_POSIX_SOCKETS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:586
msgid ""
"If 1, the POSIX sockets API uses a native bridge process server to proxy "
"sockets calls from browser to native world."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:594
msgid "NODERAWSOCKETS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:596
msgid ""
"If enabled, the POSIX sockets API is backed by Node.js's ``node:net`` "
"module, giving real non-blocking outgoing TCP sockets with no WebSockets, "
"proxy process or pthreads. This is the sockets counterpart to :ref:"
"`NODERAWFS`: where :ref:`NODERAWFS` gives direct access to the host "
"filesystem, this gives direct access to host sockets. It only works under "
"node and is ignored elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:603
msgid ""
"It supports full TCP (outgoing connect plus bind, listen and accept for "
"servers) and UDP. TCP clients use the public ``node:net`` API when possible, "
"falling back to the private ``tcp_wrap``/``udp_wrap`` handles on older Node."
"js."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:608
msgid ""
"It is event-driven. Socket readiness comes through the same "
"``emscripten_set_socket_*_callback`` hooks the WebSocket backend uses, so it "
"works with existing readiness reactors. It cannot be combined with the "
"WebSocket emulation, :ref:`PROXY_POSIX_SOCKETS` or :ref:`SOCKET_WEBRTC`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:613
msgid ""
"It works under -pthread with :ref:`PROXY_TO_PTHREAD`, where main() and every "
"socket syscall run on a single worker alongside the node handles and their "
"event loop. As with the WebSocket backend, sharing a socket across threads "
"under a plain -pthread build (without PROXY_TO_PTHREAD) is not supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:623
msgid "WEBSOCKET_SUBPROTOCOL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:625
msgid ""
"A string containing a comma separated list of WebSocket subprotocols as "
"would be present in the Sec-WebSocket-Protocol header. You can set 'null', "
"if you don't want to specify it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:629
msgid "Default value: 'binary'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:634
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3315
msgid "OPENAL_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:636
msgid "Print out debugging information from our OpenAL implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:643
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3318
msgid "WEBSOCKET_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:645
msgid ""
"If 1, prints out debugging related to calls from ``emscripten_web_socket_*`` "
"functions in ``emscripten/websocket.h``. If 2, additionally traces bytes "
"communicated via the sockets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:654
msgid "GL_ASSERTIONS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:656
msgid ""
"Adds extra checks for error situations in the GL library. Can impact "
"performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:664
msgid "TRACE_WEBGL_CALLS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:666
msgid ""
"If enabled, prints out all API calls to WebGL contexts. (*very* verbose)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:673
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3314
msgid "GL_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:675
msgid ""
"Enables more verbose debug printing of WebGL related operations. As with "
"LIBRARY_DEBUG, this is toggleable at runtime with option GL.debug."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:683
msgid "GL_TESTING"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:685
msgid ""
"When enabled, sets preserveDrawingBuffer in the context, to allow tests to "
"work (but adds overhead)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:693
msgid "GL_MAX_TEMP_BUFFER_SIZE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:695
msgid "How large GL emulation temp buffers are"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:697
msgid "Default value: 2097152"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:702
msgid "GL_UNSAFE_OPTS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:704
msgid "Enables some potentially-unsafe optimizations in GL emulation code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:711
msgid "FULL_ES2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:713
msgid ""
"Forces support for all GLES2 features, not just the WebGL-friendly subset."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:720
msgid "GL_EMULATE_GLES_VERSION_STRING_FORMAT"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:722
msgid ""
"If true, glGetString() for GL_VERSION and GL_SHADING_LANGUAGE_VERSION will "
"return strings OpenGL ES format \"Open GL ES ... (WebGL ...)\" rather than "
"the WebGL format. If false, the direct WebGL format strings are returned. "
"Set this to true to make GL contexts appear like an OpenGL ES context in "
"these version strings (at the expense of a little bit of added code size), "
"and to false to make GL contexts appear like WebGL contexts and to save some "
"bytes from the output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:735
msgid "GL_EXTENSIONS_IN_PREFIXED_FORMAT"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:737
msgid ""
"If true, all GL extensions are advertised in unprefixed WebGL extension "
"format, but also in desktop/mobile GLES/GL extension format with ``GL_`` "
"prefix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:746
msgid "GL_SUPPORT_AUTOMATIC_ENABLE_EXTENSIONS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:748
msgid ""
"If true, adds support for automatically enabling all GL extensions for GLES/"
"GL emulation purposes. This takes up code size. If you set this to 0, you "
"will need to manually enable the extensions you need."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:757
msgid "GL_SUPPORT_SIMPLE_ENABLE_EXTENSIONS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:759
msgid ""
"If true, the function ``emscripten_webgl_enable_extension()`` can be called "
"to enable any WebGL extension. If false, to save code size, "
"``emscripten_webgl_enable_extension()`` cannot be called to enable any of "
"extensions 'ANGLE_instanced_arrays', 'OES_vertex_array_object', "
"'WEBGL_draw_buffers', 'WEBGL_multi_draw', "
"'WEBGL_draw_instanced_base_vertex_base_instance', or "
"'WEBGL_multi_draw_instanced_base_vertex_base_instance', but the dedicated "
"functions ``emscripten_webgl_enable_*()`` found in html5.h are used to "
"enable each of those extensions. This way code size is increased only for "
"the extensions that are actually used. N.B. if setting this to 0, "
"GL_SUPPORT_AUTOMATIC_ENABLE_EXTENSIONS must be set to zero as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:777
msgid "GL_TRACK_ERRORS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:779
msgid ""
"If set to 0, Emscripten GLES2->WebGL translation layer does not track the "
"kind of GL errors that exist in GLES2 but do not exist in WebGL. Setting "
"this to 0 saves code size. (Good to keep at 1 for development)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:788
msgid "GL_SUPPORT_EXPLICIT_SWAP_CONTROL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:790
msgid ""
"If true, GL contexts support the explicitSwapControl context creation flag. "
"Set to 0 to save a little bit of space on projects that do not need it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:798
msgid "GL_POOL_TEMP_BUFFERS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:800
msgid ""
"If true, calls to glUniform*fv and glUniformMatrix*fv utilize a pool of "
"preallocated temporary buffers for common small sizes to avoid generating "
"temporary garbage for WebGL 1. Disable this to optimize generated size of "
"the GL library a little bit, at the expense of generating garbage in WebGL "
"1. If you are only using WebGL 2 and do not support WebGL 1, this is not "
"needed and you can turn it off."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:812
msgid "GL_EXPLICIT_UNIFORM_LOCATION"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:814
msgid ""
"If true, enables support for the EMSCRIPTEN_explicit_uniform_location WebGL "
"extension. See docs/EMSCRIPTEN_explicit_uniform_location.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:822
msgid "GL_EXPLICIT_UNIFORM_BINDING"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:824
msgid ""
"If true, enables support for the EMSCRIPTEN_uniform_layout_binding WebGL "
"extension. See docs/EMSCRIPTEN_explicit_uniform_binding.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:832
msgid "USE_WEBGL2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:834
msgid "Deprecated. Pass -sMAX_WEBGL_VERSION=2 to target WebGL 2.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:841
msgid "MIN_WEBGL_VERSION"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:843
msgid ""
"Specifies the lowest WebGL version to target. Pass -sMIN_WEBGL_VERSION=1 to "
"enable targeting WebGL 1, and -sMIN_WEBGL_VERSION=2 to drop support for "
"WebGL 1.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:852
msgid "MAX_WEBGL_VERSION"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:854
msgid ""
"Specifies the highest WebGL version to target. Pass -sMAX_WEBGL_VERSION=2 to "
"enable targeting WebGL 2. If WebGL 2 is enabled, some APIs (EGL, GLUT, SDL) "
"will default to creating a WebGL 2 context if no version is specified. Note "
"that there is no automatic fallback to WebGL1 if WebGL2 is not supported by "
"the user's device, even if you build with both WebGL1 and WebGL2 support, as "
"that may not always be what the application wants. If you want such a "
"fallback, you can try to create a context with WebGL2, and if that fails try "
"to create one with WebGL1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:868
msgid "WEBGL2_BACKWARDS_COMPATIBILITY_EMULATION"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:870
msgid ""
"If true, emulates some WebGL 1 features on WebGL 2 contexts, meaning that "
"applications that use WebGL 1/GLES 2 can initialize a WebGL 2/GLES3 context, "
"but still keep using WebGL1/GLES 2 functionality that no longer is supported "
"in WebGL2/GLES3. Currently this emulates GL_EXT_shader_texture_lod extension "
"in GLSL ES 1.00 shaders, support for unsized internal texture formats, and "
"the GL_HALF_FLOAT_OES != GL_HALF_FLOAT mixup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:882
msgid "FULL_ES3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:884
msgid ""
"Forces support for all GLES3 features, not just the WebGL2-friendly subset. "
"This automatically turns on FULL_ES2 and WebGL2 support."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:892
msgid "LEGACY_GL_EMULATION"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:894
msgid ""
"Includes code to emulate various desktop GL features. Incomplete but useful "
"in some cases, see http://kripken.github.io/emscripten-site/docs/porting/"
"multimedia_and_graphics/OpenGL-support.html"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:903
msgid "GL_FFP_ONLY"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:905
msgid ""
"If you specified LEGACY_GL_EMULATION = 1 and only use fixed function "
"pipeline in your code, you can also set this to 1 to signal the GL emulation "
"layer that it can perform extra optimizations by knowing that the user code "
"does not use shaders at all. If LEGACY_GL_EMULATION = 0, this setting has no "
"effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:916
msgid "GL_PREINITIALIZED_CONTEXT"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:918
msgid ""
"If you want to create the WebGL context up front in JS code, set this to 1 "
"and set Module['preinitializedWebGLContext'] to a precreated WebGL context. "
"WebGL initialization afterwards will use this GL context to render."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:927
msgid "STB_IMAGE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:929
msgid ""
"Enables building of stb-image, a tiny public-domain library for decoding "
"images, allowing decoding of images without using the browser's built-in "
"decoders. The benefit is that this can be done synchronously, however, it "
"will not be as fast as the browser itself.  When enabled, stb-image will be "
"used automatically from IMG_Load and IMG_Load_RW. You can also call the "
"``stbi_*`` functions directly yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:941
msgid "GL_DISABLE_HALF_FLOAT_EXTENSION_IF_BROKEN"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:943
msgid ""
"From Safari 8 (where WebGL was introduced to Safari) onwards, "
"OES_texture_half_float and OES_texture_half_float_linear extensions are "
"broken and do not function correctly, when used as source textures. See "
"https://webkit.org/b/183321, https://webkit.org/b/169999, https://"
"stackoverflow.com/questions/54248633/cannot-create-half-float-oes-texture-"
"from-uint16array-on-ipad"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:953
msgid "GL_WORKAROUND_SAFARI_GETCONTEXT_BUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:955
msgid ""
"Workaround Safari WebGL issue: After successfully acquiring WebGL context on "
"a canvas, calling .getContext() will always return that context independent "
"of which 'webgl' or 'webgl2' context version was passed. See https://webkit."
"org/b/222758 and https://github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/issues/13295. "
"Set this to 0 to force-disable the workaround if you know the issue will not "
"affect you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:966
msgid "GL_ENABLE_GET_PROC_ADDRESS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:968
msgid ""
"If 1, link with support to glGetProcAddress() functionality. In WebGL, "
"glGetProcAddress() causes a substantial code size and performance impact, "
"since WebGL does not natively provide such functionality, and it must be "
"emulated. Using glGetProcAddress() is not recommended. If you still need to "
"use this, e.g. when porting an existing renderer, you can link with -"
"sGL_ENABLE_GET_PROC_ADDRESS to get support for this functionality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:979
msgid "JS_MATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:981
msgid ""
"Use JavaScript math functions like Math.tan. This saves code size as we can "
"avoid shipping compiled musl code. However, it can be significantly slower "
"as it calls out to JS. It also may give different results as JS math is "
"specced somewhat differently than libc, and can also vary between browsers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:991
msgid "LEGACY_VM_SUPPORT"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:993
msgid ""
"Set this to enable compatibility emulations for old JavaScript engines. This "
"gives you the highest possible probability of the code working everywhere, "
"even in rare old browsers and shell environments. Specifically:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:997
msgid "Disable WebAssembly. (Must be paired with -sWASM=0)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:998
msgid ""
"Adjusts MIN_X_VERSION settings to 0 to include support for all browser "
"versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:999
msgid "Avoid TypedArray.fill, if necessary, in zeroMemory utility function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1001
msgid "You can also configure the above options individually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1008
msgid "ENVIRONMENT"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1010
msgid ""
"Specify which runtime environments the JS output will be capable of running "
"in.  For maximum portability this can be configured to support all "
"environments or it can be limited to reduce overall code size.  The "
"supported environments are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1015
msgid "'web'     - the normal web environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1016
msgid ""
"'webview' - just like web, but in a webview like Cordova; considered to be "
"same as \"web\" in almost every place"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1018
msgid "'worker'  - a web worker environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1019
msgid "'worklet' - Audio Worklet environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1020
msgid "'node'    - Node.js."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1021
msgid "'shell'   - a JS shell like d8, js, or jsc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1023
msgid ""
"This setting can be a comma-separated list of these environments, e.g., "
"\"web,worker\". If this is the empty string, then all environments are "
"supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1027
msgid ""
"Certain settings will automatically add to this list.  For examble, building "
"with pthreads will automatically add `worker` and building with "
"``AUDIO_WORKLET`` will automatically add `worklet`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1031
msgid ""
"Note that the set of environments recognized here is not identical to the "
"ones we identify at runtime using ``ENVIRONMENT_IS_*``. Specifically:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1034
msgid ""
"We detect whether we are a pthread at runtime, but that's set for workers "
"and not for the main file so it wouldn't make sense to specify here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1036
msgid ""
"The webview target is basically a subset of web. It must be specified "
"alongside web (e.g. \"web,webview\") and we only use it for code generation "
"at compile time, there is no runtime behavior change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1040
msgid ""
"Note that by default we do not include the 'shell' environment since direct "
"usage of d8, spidermonkey and jsc is extremely rare."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1043
msgid "Default value: ['web', 'webview', 'worker', 'node']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1048
msgid "LZ4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1050
msgid ""
"Enable this to support lz4-compressed file packages. They are stored "
"compressed in memory, and decompressed on the fly, avoiding storing the "
"entire decompressed data in memory at once. If you run the file packager "
"separately, you still need to build the main program with this flag, and "
"also pass --lz4 to the file packager. (You can also manually compress one on "
"the client, using LZ4.loadPackage(), but that is less recommended.) "
"Limitations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1058
msgid ""
"LZ4-compressed files are only decompressed when needed, so they are not "
"available for special preloading operations like pre-decoding of images "
"using browser codecs, preloadPlugin stuff, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1061
msgid "LZ4 files are read-only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1068
msgid "DISABLE_EXCEPTION_CATCHING"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1070
msgid ""
"Disables generating code to actually catch exceptions. This disabling is on "
"by default as the overhead of exceptions is quite high in size and speed "
"currently (in the future, wasm should improve that). When exceptions are "
"disabled, if an exception actually happens then it will not be caught and "
"the program will halt (so this will not introduce silent failures)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1078
msgid ""
"This removes *catching* of exceptions, which is the main issue for speed, "
"but you should build source files with -fno-exceptions to really get rid of "
"all exceptions code overhead, as it may contain thrown exceptions that are "
"never caught (e.g. just using std::vector can have that). -fno-rtti may help "
"as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1084
msgid ""
"This option is mutually exclusive with :ref:`EXCEPTION_CATCHING_ALLOWED`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1086
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1103
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1126
msgid ""
"This option only applies to Emscripten (JavaScript-based) exception handling "
"and does not control the native Wasm exception handling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1096
msgid "EXCEPTION_CATCHING_ALLOWED"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1098
msgid ""
"Enables catching exception but only in the listed functions.  This option "
"acts like a more precise version of ``DISABLE_EXCEPTION_CATCHING=0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1101
msgid ""
"This option is mutually exclusive with :ref:`DISABLE_EXCEPTION_CATCHING`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1108
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1225
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1293
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1310
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1335
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1367
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1395
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1409
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1423
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1590
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1645
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1700
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:2443
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3123
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:3348
msgid "Default value: []"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1113
msgid "DISABLE_EXCEPTION_THROWING"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1115
msgid ""
"Internal: Tracks whether Emscripten should link in exception throwing (C++ "
"'throw') support library. This does not need to be set directly, but pass -"
"fno-exceptions to the build disable exceptions support. (This is basically -"
"fno-exceptions, but checked at final link time instead of individual .cpp "
"file compile time) If the program *does* contain throwing code (some source "
"files were not compiled with ``-fno-exceptions``), and this flag is set at "
"link time, then you will get errors on undefined symbols, as the exception "
"throwing code is not linked in. If so you should either unset the option (if "
"you do want exceptions) or fix the compilation of the source files so that "
"indeed no exceptions are used)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1136
msgid "EXPORT_EXCEPTION_HANDLING_HELPERS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1138
msgid ""
"Make the exception message printing function, 'getExceptionMessage' "
"available in the JS library for use, by adding necessary symbols to :ref:"
"`EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1142
msgid ""
"This works with both Emscripten EH and Wasm EH. When you catch an exception "
"from JS, that gives you a user-thrown value in case of Emscripten EH, and a "
"WebAssembly.Exception object in case of Wasm EH. 'getExceptionMessage' takes "
"the user-thrown value in case of Emscripten EH and the WebAssembly.Exception "
"object in case of Wasm EH, meaning in both cases you can pass a caught "
"exception directly to the function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1149
msgid ""
"When used with Wasm EH, this option additionally provides these functions in "
"the JS library:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1152
msgid "getCppExceptionTag: Returns the C++ tag"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1153
msgid ""
"getCppExceptionThrownObjectFromWebAssemblyException: Given an WebAssembly."
"Exception object, returns the actual user-thrown C++ object address in Wasm "
"memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1157
msgid ""
"Setting this option also adds refcount incrementing and decrementing "
"functions ('incrementExceptionRefcount' and 'decrementExceptionRefcount') in "
"the JS library because if you catch an exception from JS, you may need to "
"manipulate the refcount manually to avoid memory leaks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1162
msgid ""
"See test_EXPORT_EXCEPTION_HANDLING_HELPERS in test/test_core.py for an "
"example usage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1172
msgid "EXCEPTION_STACK_TRACES"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1174
msgid ""
"When this is enabled, exceptions will contain stack traces and uncaught "
"exceptions will display stack traces upon exiting. This defaults to true "
"when ASSERTIONS is enabled. This option is for users who want exceptions' "
"stack traces but do not want other overheads ASSERTIONS can incur. This "
"option implies :ref:`EXPORT_EXCEPTION_HANDLING_HELPERS`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1185
msgid "WASM_LEGACY_EXCEPTIONS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1187
msgid ""
"If true, emit instructions for the legacy Wasm exception handling proposal: "
"https://github.com/WebAssembly/exception-handling/blob/main/proposals/"
"exception-handling/legacy/Exceptions.md If false, emit instructions for the "
"standardized exception handling proposal: https://github.com/WebAssembly/"
"exception-handling/blob/main/proposals/exception-handling/Exceptions.md"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1199
msgid "ASYNCIFY"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1201
msgid ""
"Whether to support async operations in the compiled code. This makes it "
"possible to call JS functions from synchronous-looking code in C/C++."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1204
msgid ""
"1 (default): Run binaryen's Asyncify pass to transform the code using "
"asyncify. This emits a normal wasm file in the end, so it works everywhere, "
"but it has a significant cost in terms of code size and speed. See https://"
"emscripten.org/docs/porting/asyncify.html"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1208
msgid "2 (deprecated): Use ``-sJSPI`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1215
msgid "ASYNCIFY_IMPORTS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1217
msgid ""
"Imports which can do an async operation, in addition to the default ones "
"that emscripten defines like emscripten_sleep. If you add more you will need "
"to mention them to here, or else they will not work (in :ref:`ASSERTIONS` "
"builds an error will be shown). Note that this list used to contain the "
"default ones, which meant that you had to list them when adding your own; "
"the default ones are now added automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1230
msgid "ASYNCIFY_IGNORE_INDIRECT"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1232
msgid ""
"Whether indirect calls can be on the stack during an unwind/rewind. If you "
"know they cannot, then setting this can be extremely helpful, as otherwise "
"asyncify must assume an indirect call can reach almost everywhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1241
msgid "ASYNCIFY_STACK_SIZE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1243
msgid ""
"The size of the asyncify stack - the region used to store unwind/rewind "
"info. This must be large enough to store the call stack and locals. If it is "
"too small, you will see a wasm trap due to executing an \"unreachable\" "
"instruction. In that case, you should increase this size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1248
msgid "Default value: 4096"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1253
msgid "ASYNCIFY_REMOVE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1255
msgid ""
"If the Asyncify remove-list is provided, then the functions in it will not "
"be instrumented even if it looks like they need to. This can be useful if "
"you know things the whole-program analysis doesn't, like if you know certain "
"indirect calls are safe and won't unwind. But if you get the list wrong "
"things will break (and in a production build user input might reach code "
"paths you missed during testing, so it's hard to know you got this right), "
"so this is not recommended unless you really know what are doing, and need "
"to optimize every bit of speed and size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1265
msgid ""
"The names in this list are names from the WebAssembly Names section. The "
"wasm backend will emit those names in *human-readable* form instead of "
"typical C++ mangling. For example, you should write ``Struct::func()`` "
"instead of ``_ZN6Struct4FuncEv``. C is also different from C++, as C names "
"don't end with parameters; as a result foo(int) in C++ would appear as just "
"foo in C (C++ has parameters because it needs to differentiate overloaded "
"functions). You will see warnings in the console if a name in the list is "
"missing (these are not errors because inlining etc. may cause changes which "
"would mean a single list couldn't work for both -O0 and -O1 builds, etc.). "
"You can inspect the wasm binary to look for the actual names, either "
"directly or using wasm-objdump or wasm-dis, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1277
msgid "Simple ``*`` wildcard matching is supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1279
msgid ""
"To avoid dealing with limitations in operating system shells or build system "
"escaping, the following substitutions can be made:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1282
msgid "' ' -> ``.``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1283
msgid "``&`` -> ``#``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1284
msgid "``,`` -> ``?``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1286
msgid ""
"That is, the function `\"foo(char const*, int&)\"` can be inputted as "
"`\"foo(char.const*?.int#)\"` on the command line instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1289
msgid ""
"Note: Whitespace is part of the function signature! I.e. \"foo(char const *, "
"int &)\" will not match \"foo(char const*, int&)\", and neither would "
"\"foo(const char*, int &)\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1298
msgid "ASYNCIFY_ADD"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1300
msgid ""
"Functions in the Asyncify add-list are added to the list of instrumented "
"functions, that is, they will be instrumented even if otherwise asyncify "
"thinks they don't need to be. As by default everything will be instrumented "
"in the safest way possible, this is only useful if you use IGNORE_INDIRECT "
"and use this list to fix up some indirect calls that *do* need to be "
"instrumented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1307
#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1332
msgid ""
"See :ref:`ASYNCIFY_REMOVE` about the names, including wildcard matching and "
"character substitutions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1315
msgid "ASYNCIFY_PROPAGATE_ADD"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1317
msgid ""
"If enabled, instrumentation status will be propagated from the add-list, ie. "
"their callers, and their callers' callers, and so on. If disabled then all "
"callers must be manually added to the add-list (like the only-list)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1326
msgid "ASYNCIFY_ONLY"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1328
msgid ""
"If the Asyncify only-list is provided, then *only* the functions in the list "
"will be instrumented. Like the remove-list, getting this wrong will break "
"your application."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1340
msgid "ASYNCIFY_ADVISE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1342
msgid "If enabled will output which functions have been instrumented and why."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1349
msgid "ASYNCIFY_DEBUG"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1351
msgid "Runtime debug logging from asyncify internals."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1353
msgid "1: Minimal logging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1354
msgid "2: Verbose logging."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1361
msgid "ASYNCIFY_EXPORTS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1363
msgid "Deprecated, use JSPI_EXPORTS instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1372
msgid "JSPI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1374
msgid ""
"Use VM support for the JavaScript Promise Integration proposal. This allows "
"async operations to happen without the overhead of modifying the wasm. This "
"is experimental at the moment while spec discussion is ongoing, see https://"
"github.com/WebAssembly/js-promise-integration/ TODO: document which of the "
"following flags are still relevant in this mode (e.g. IGNORE_INDIRECT etc. "
"are not needed)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1386
msgid "JSPI_EXPORTS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1388
msgid ""
"A list of exported module functions that will be asynchronous. Each export "
"will return a ``Promise`` that will be resolved with the result. Any exports "
"that will call an asynchronous import (listed in ``JSPI_IMPORTS``) must be "
"included here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1393
msgid "By default this includes ``main``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1400
msgid "JSPI_IMPORTS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1402
msgid ""
"A list of imported module functions that will potentially do asynchronous "
"work. The imported function should return a ``Promise`` when doing "
"asynchronous work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1406
msgid ""
"Note when using JS library files, the function can be marked with "
"``<function_name>_async:: true`` in the library instead of this setting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1414
msgid "EXPORTED_RUNTIME_METHODS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1416
msgid ""
"Runtime elements that are exported on Module by default. We used to export "
"quite a lot here, but have removed them all. You should use "
"EXPORTED_RUNTIME_METHODS for things you want to export from the runtime. "
"Note that the name may be slightly misleading, as this is for any JS library "
"element, and not just methods. For example, we can export the FS object by "
"having \"FS\" in this list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1428
msgid "INCOMING_MODULE_JS_API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1430
msgid ""
"A list of incoming values on the Module object in JS that we care about. If "
"a value is not in this list, then we don't emit code to check if you provide "
"it on the Module object. For example, if you have this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1440
msgid ""
"Then INCOMING_MODULE_JS_API must contain 'print' and 'preRun'; if it does "
"not then we may not emit code to read and use that value. In other words, "
"this option lets you set, statically at compile time, the list of which "
"Module JS values you will be providing at runtime, so the compiler can "
"better optimize."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1446
msgid ""
"Setting this list to [], or at least a short and concise set of names you "
"actually use, can be very useful for reducing code size. By default, the "
"list contains a set of commonly used symbols."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1450
msgid "In addition to the default symbols, the following are also available:"
msgstr ""

