msgid "forcedAspectRatio"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1474
msgid "mainScriptUrlOrBlob"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1475
msgid "onFullScreen"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1477
msgid "wasmMemory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1478
msgid "wasmBinary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1480
msgid "Default value: (multi-line value, see settings.js)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1485
msgid "CASE_INSENSITIVE_FS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1487
msgid ""
"If set to nonzero, the provided virtual filesystem is treated case-"
"insensitive, like Windows and macOS do. If set to 0, the VFS is case-"
"sensitive, like on Linux."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1496
msgid "FILESYSTEM"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1498
msgid ""
"If set to 0, does not build in any filesystem support. Useful if you are "
"just doing pure computation, but not reading files or using any streams "
"(including fprintf, and other stdio.h things) or anything related. The one "
"exception is there is partial support for printf, and puts, hackishly.  The "
"compiler will automatically set this if it detects that syscall usage (which "
"is static) does not require a full filesystem. If you still want filesystem "
"support, use FORCE_FILESYSTEM"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1511
msgid "FORCE_FILESYSTEM"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1513
msgid ""
"Makes full filesystem support be included, even if statically it looks like "
"it is not used. For example, if your C code uses no files, but you include "
"some JS that does, you might need this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1522
msgid "NODERAWFS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1524
msgid ""
"Enables support for the ``NODERAWFS`` filesystem backend. This is a special "
"backend as it replaces all normal filesystem access with direct Node.js "
"operations, without the need to do ``FS.mount()``, and this backend only "
"works with Node.js. The initial working directory will be same as process."
"cwd() instead of VFS root directory.  Because this mode directly uses Node."
"js to access the real local filesystem on your OS, the code will not "
"necessarily be portable between OSes - it will be as portable as a Node.js "
"program would be, which means that differences in how the underlying OS "
"handles permissions and errors and so forth may be noticeable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1534
msgid "Enabling this setting will also enable :ref:`NODE_HOST_ENV` by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1541
msgid "NODE_HOST_ENV"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1543
msgid ""
"When running under Node, expose the underlying OS environment variables. "
"This is similar to how ``NODERAWFS`` exposes the underlying FS. This setting "
"gets enabled by default when ``NODERAWFS`` is enabled, but can also be "
"controlled separately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1553
msgid "NODE_CODE_CACHING"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1555
msgid ""
"This saves the compiled wasm module in a file with name ``$WASM_BINARY_NAME."
"$V8_VERSION.cached`` and loads it on subsequent runs. This caches the "
"compiled wasm code from v8 in node, which saves compiling on subsequent "
"runs, making them start up much faster. The V8 version used in node is "
"included in the cache name so that we don't try to load cached code from "
"another version, which fails silently (it seems to load ok, but we do "
"actually recompile)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1564
msgid ""
"The only version known to work for sure is node 12.9.1, as this has "
"regressed, see https://github.com/nodejs/node/"
"issues/18265#issuecomment-622971547"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1567
msgid ""
"The default location of the .cached files is alongside the wasm binary, as "
"mentioned earlier. If that is in a read-only directory, you may need to "
"place them elsewhere. You can use the locateFile() hook to do so."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1576
msgid "EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1578
msgid ""
"Symbols that are explicitly exported. These symbols are kept alive through "
"LLVM dead code elimination, and also made accessible outside of the "
"generated code even after running closure compiler (on \"Module\").  Native "
"symbols listed here require an ``_`` prefix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1583
msgid ""
"By default if this setting is not specified on the command line the "
"``_main`` function will be implicitly exported.  In :ref:`STANDALONE_WASM` "
"mode the default export is ``__start`` (or ``__initialize`` if ``--no-"
"entry`` is specified)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1588
msgid ""
"JS Library symbols can also be added to this list (without the leading `$`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1595
msgid "EXPORT_ALL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1597
msgid ""
"If true, we export all the symbols that are present in JS onto the Module "
"object. This does not affect which symbols will be present - it does not "
"prevent DCE or cause anything to be included in linking. It only does "
"``Module['X'] = X;`` for all X that end up in the JS file. This is useful to "
"export the JS library functions on Module, for things like dynamic linking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1609
msgid "EXPORT_KEEPALIVE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1611
msgid ""
"If true, we export the symbols that are present in JS onto the Module "
"object. It only does ``Module['X'] = X;``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1620
msgid "RETAIN_COMPILER_SETTINGS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1622
msgid ""
"Remembers the values of these settings, and makes them accessible through "
"getCompilerSetting and emscripten_get_compiler_setting. To see what is "
"retained, look for compilerSettings in the generated code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1631
msgid "DEFAULT_LIBRARY_FUNCS_TO_INCLUDE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1633
msgid ""
"JS library elements (C functions implemented in JS) that we include by "
"default.  If you want to make sure something is included by the JS compiler, "
"add it here.  For example, if you do not use some ``emscripten_*`` C API "
"call from C, but you want to call it from JS, add it here. Note that the "
"name may be slightly misleading, as this is for any JS library element, and "
"not just functions. For example, you can include the Browser object by "
"adding \"$Browser\" to this list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1641
msgid ""
"If you want to both include and export a JS library symbol, it is enough to "
"simply add it to EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS, without also adding it to "
"DEFAULT_LIBRARY_FUNCS_TO_INCLUDE."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1650
msgid "INCLUDE_FULL_LIBRARY"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1652
msgid ""
"Include all JS library functions instead of the sum of "
"DEFAULT_LIBRARY_FUNCS_TO_INCLUDE + any functions used by the generated code. "
"This is needed when dynamically loading (i.e. dlopen) modules that make use "
"of runtime library functions that are not used in the main module.  Note "
"that this only applies to js libraries, *not* C. You will need the main file "
"to include all needed C libraries.  For example, if a module uses malloc or "
"new, you will need to use those in the main file too to pull in malloc for "
"use by the module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1666
msgid "MAIN_MODULE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1668
msgid ""
"A main module is a file compiled in a way that allows us to link it to a "
"side module at runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1671
msgid "1: Normal main module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1672
msgid ""
"2: DCE'd main module. We eliminate dead code normally. If a side module "
"needs something from main, it is up to you to make sure it is kept alive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1683
msgid "SIDE_MODULE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1685
msgid "Corresponds to MAIN_MODULE (also supports modes 1 and 2)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1694
msgid "RUNTIME_LINKED_LIBS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1696
msgid "Deprecated, list shared libraries directly on the command line instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1705
msgid "BUILD_AS_WORKER"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1707
msgid ""
"If set to 1, this is a worker library, a special kind of library that is run "
"in a worker. See emscripten.h"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1715
msgid "PROXY_TO_PTHREAD"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1717
msgid ""
"If set to 1, compiles in a small stub main() in between the real main() "
"which calls pthread_create() to run the application main() in a pthread.  "
"This is something that applications can do manually as well if they wish, "
"this option is provided as convenience."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1722
msgid ""
"The pthread that main() runs on is a normal pthread in all ways, with the "
"one difference that its stack size is the same as the main thread would "
"normally have, that is, STACK_SIZE. This makes it easy to flip between "
"PROXY_TO_PTHREAD and non-PROXY_TO_PTHREAD modes with main() always getting "
"the same amount of stack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1728
msgid ""
"This proxies Module['canvas'], if present, and if OFFSCREENCANVAS_SUPPORT is "
"enabled. This has to happen because this is the only chance - this browser "
"main thread does the only pthread_create call that happens on that thread, "
"so it's the only chance to transfer the canvas from there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1738
msgid "LINKABLE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1740
msgid ""
"If set to 1, this file can be linked with others, either as a shared library "
"or as the main file that calls a shared library. To enable that, we will not "
"internalize all symbols and cull the unused ones, in other words, we will "
"not remove unused functions and globals, which might be used by another "
"module we are linked with."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1746
msgid ""
"MAIN_MODULE and SIDE_MODULE both imply this, so it not normally necessary to "
"set this explicitly. Note that MAIN_MODULE and SIDE_MODULE mode 2 do *not* "
"set this, so that we still do normal DCE on them, and in that case you must "
"keep relevant things alive yourself using exporting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1760
msgid "STRICT"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1762
msgid ""
"Emscripten 'strict' build mode: Drop supporting any deprecated build "
"options. Set the environment variable EMCC_STRICT=1 or pass -sSTRICT to test "
"that a codebase builds nicely in forward compatible manner. Changes enabled "
"by this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1767
msgid "STRICT_JS is enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1768
msgid "IGNORE_MISSING_MAIN is disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1769
msgid "AUTO_JS_LIBRARIES is disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1770
msgid "AUTO_NATIVE_LIBRARIES is disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1771
msgid "DEFAULT_TO_CXX is disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1772
msgid "ALLOW_UNIMPLEMENTED_SYSCALLS is disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1773
msgid "INCOMING_MODULE_JS_API is set to empty by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1782
msgid "IGNORE_MISSING_MAIN"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1784
msgid ""
"Allow program to link with or without ``main`` symbol. If this is disabled "
"then one must provide a ``main`` symbol or explicitly opt out by passing ``--"
"no-entry`` or an EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS list that doesn't include ``_main``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1794
msgid "STRICT_JS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1796
msgid "Add ``\"use strict;\"`` to generated JS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1803
msgid "WARN_ON_UNDEFINED_SYMBOLS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1805
msgid ""
"If set to 1, we will warn on any undefined symbols that are not resolved by "
"the ``library_*.js`` files. Note that it is common in large projects to not "
"implement everything, when you know what is not going to actually be called "
"(and don't want to mess with the existing buildsystem), and functions might "
"be implemented later on, say in --pre-js, so you may want to build with -s "
"WARN_ON_UNDEFINED_SYMBOLS=0 to disable the warnings if they annoy you.  See "
"also ERROR_ON_UNDEFINED_SYMBOLS.  Any undefined symbols that are listed in "
"EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS will also be reported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1819
msgid "ERROR_ON_UNDEFINED_SYMBOLS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1821
msgid ""
"If set to 1, we will give a link-time error on any undefined symbols (see "
"WARN_ON_UNDEFINED_SYMBOLS). To allow undefined symbols at link time set this "
"to 0, in which case if an undefined function is called a runtime error will "
"occur.  Any undefined symbols that are listed in EXPORTED_FUNCTIONS will "
"also be reported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1832
msgid "SMALL_XHR_CHUNKS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1834
msgid ""
"Use small chunk size for binary synchronous XHR's in Web Workers.  Used for "
"testing.  See test_chunked_synchronous_xhr in runner.py and library.js."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1842
msgid "MODULARIZE"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1844
msgid ""
"By default we emit all code in a straightforward way into the output .js "
"file. That means that if you load that in a script tag in a web page, it "
"will use the global scope. With ``MODULARIZE`` set, we instead emit the code "
"wrapped in an async function. This function returns a promise that resolves "
"to a module instance once it is safe to run the compiled code (similar to "
"the ``onRuntimeInitialized`` callback)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1851
msgid ""
"The default name of the function is ``Module``, but can be changed using the "
"``EXPORT_NAME`` option. We recommend renaming it to a more typical name for "
"a factory function, e.g. ``createModule``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1855
msgid "You use the factory function like so::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1859
msgid "or::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1867
msgid ""
"The factory function accepts 1 parameter, an object with default values for "
"the module instance::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1872
msgid ""
"Note the parentheses - we are calling EXPORT_NAME in order to instantiate "
"the module. This allows you to create multiple instances of the module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1875
msgid ""
"Note that in MODULARIZE mode we do *not* look for a global ``Module`` object "
"for default values. Default values must be passed as a parameter to the "
"factory function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1879
msgid ""
"The default .html shell file provided in MINIMAL_RUNTIME mode will create a "
"singleton instance automatically, to run the application on the page. (Note "
"that it does so without using the Promise API mentioned earlier, and so code "
"for the Promise is not even emitted in the .js file if you tell emcc to emit "
"an .html output.) The default .html shell file provided by traditional "
"runtime mode is only compatible with MODULARIZE=0 mode, so when building "
"with traditional runtime, you should provided your own html shell file to "
"perform the instantiation when building with MODULARIZE=1. (For more "
"details, see https://github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/issues/7950)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1890
msgid ""
"If you add --pre-js or --post-js files, they will be included inside the "
"factory function with the rest of the emitted code in order to be optimized "
"together with it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1894
msgid ""
"If you want to include code outside all of the generated code, including the "
"factory function, you can use --extern-pre-js or --extern-post-js. While --"
"pre-js and --post-js happen to do that in non-MODULARIZE mode, their "
"intended usage is to add code that is optimized with the rest of the emitted "
"code, allowing better dead code elimination and minification."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1900
msgid "Experimental Feature - Instance ES Modules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1902
msgid ""
"Note this feature is still under active development and is subject to change!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1904
msgid ""
"To enable this feature use -sMODULARIZE=instance. Enabling this mode will "
"produce an ES module that is a singleton with ES module exports. The module "
"will export a default value that is an async init function and will also "
"export named values that correspond to the Wasm exports and runtime exports. "
"The init function must be called before any of the exports can be used. An "
"example of using the module is below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.rst:1911
msgid ""
